Ovarian cancer is more often killed in sparsely populated areas due to a late diagnosis and access to treatment
Angelina Jolie and her brother James have released the video as a tribute to her mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women living in rural Australia are at higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
The researchers reviewed the medical records of more than 1100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005 and found that only 35 percent of women lived more than five years after the diagnosis.
Susan Jordan QIMR of the Berghofer Medical Research Institute confirms that women living in sparsely populated and remote areas were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than women living in urban areas.
SMALL RESEARCH: New drugs may slow down lung and ovarian cancer
The researchers reviewed the health history of women over a period of seven years.
According to doctor Susan Jordan, the age of the woman at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, previous diseases and socioeconomic status also affected the chances of survival.
In older women and when the cancer was more widespread at the time of diagnosis, the chances of survival were the lowest.
Women living in sparsely populated and remote areas were 20 per cent more likely to die during the study than women living in urban areas.
The study did not seek to determine why women living outside cities are less likely to survive ovarian cancer, but Jordan considers the possible causes of delayed diagnosis and inconvenience of access to treatment.
“Gynecological oncology specialists treat this disease the best, and their clinics are mostly located in major cities,” Jordan says.
Although remote treatments are becoming more common and the importance of distance is diminishing, the researcher also suggests increasing the mobility of physicians so that specialists can treat patients closer to their home, as well as programs to support patients treated far from home.
According to a study by Dr. Jordan, the long-term survival rate of women with ovarian cancer is poor regardless of their geographical location, which emphasizes the need for better treatment and better cancer prevention programs.
The study, funded by the Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer charity, is published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, 33-year-old mother Elisha Neave, a 33-year-old mother from Gold Coast, was diagnosed with malignant ovarian cancer.
