A genetic abnormality is often misdiagnosed
For years, a British woman was afraid of dying because of a wrong diagnosis.
Karin Rodgers thought most of her youth that she only had a few years left to live because she had been diagnosed with another disease.
He actually suffered from Charcot-Marie-Tooth's disease (CMT). It means a group of hereditary diseases that damage the nerves outside the brain and spine.
According to the Charity CMT UK charity, a wrong diagnosis is a common problem in CMT cases because so little is known about them.
It is estimated that around 23 000 people in the UK suffer from CMT, which causes symptoms in motor skills, such as muscle weakness, difficult walking and toe-skinning.
The disease can also cause numbness or pain, and it is incurable and progressive, which means that the symptoms worsen over time.
When Rodgers was 13, he thought he had Friedreich's ataxia (FA), which has a really poor survival rate.
Rodgers believed he would be in a wheelchair before turning 18 and die before reaching the age of 30.
Today, the 51-year-old mother of two says, “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do the same things as everyone else.
I fell down every day and it took me longer than everyone else.
I could never skate or skate with other kids, and I was bullied at school because I was walking and running differently than everyone else.
When Rodgers was 13 years old, he underwent several Achilles tendon surgeries to straighten his legs. During the surgery, after the doctor left the room, he quickly glanced at his examination papers saying that he was suffering from FA.
“I felt guilty because I was so curious, so I didn’t tell anyone, but when I got home, I checked the information about the disease in the library and wrote to the FA Association,” he says.
When I got information from them, I was shocked and in a panicky state.
I thought I was going to be in a wheelchair by the age of 18 and that I would die before I turned 25, and in between, I would slowly lose my full ability to function.
I went through this on my own and planned my own funeral.
Rodgers says that by the age of 17, he stated that his walk had not deteriorated as much as he had thought and asked his doctor about this.
The doctor just hugged me and said, “God, I don’t think you have this disease, because otherwise you’d be in a wheelchair.”
I think you're suffering from something much less dangerous.
Based on some genetic tests, he was diagnosed with CMT.
“When I was explained what CMT was, I thought I was being postponed,” he said.
